  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since women are often the most affected by these types of crises, IEDA Relief and United2Heal, a George Mason University student-led organization, decided to target women as their primary beneficiaries. Responding to the primary needs raised by female refugees, returnees, and internally displaced persons (IDPs) in the camp of Sayam in Niger, female hygiene kits, or &#x201C;dignity kits&#x201D;, were identified as crucial items to provide for thousands of women in need. The Preserving Dignity Campaign was held between March and May of 2015, and raised enough funds to supply over 60 dignity kids to the most vulnerable women in the Sayam Camp. Each kit is intended to last for 3 months and includes:</narrative>
